AsDB would like to note that it recently launched the AsDB Data Library which is the centralized repository of AsDB's public data (see: https://data.adb.org/). The portal allows one to access and download relevant data on AsDB's projects and operations as well as macroeconomic and social indicators. The ADB Data Library also links to existing dashboards on climate financing, ADB operational approvals, total population of the Asia and the Pacific, and country performance assessments.

The EIB does not operate based on forward planning budgets for individual countries or institutions. Such forward looking budgets or plans are not produced in EIB. The business model on which basis the EIB operates as a financing institution does in fact not allow such a detailed forward planning. For example, the EIB signs finance contracts with a counterpart for the financing of a particular activity. However, one cannot say at what moment these funds will actually be disbursed. It is up to the counterpart to request the disbursement. The disbursement is therefore much more demand driven as in a grant making institution.

EIB is following the specific DFI/IFI IATI implementation schedule that recognizes the specificity of financial institutions.

The EIB Corporate Operational Plan (COP) comes closest to a forward-looking planning, with indicative amounts for regions over the next three years. This has been accepted in the past by PWYF as sufficient to score on this indicator. The Corporate Operational Plan is published in EIBs IATI organizational file.

Portals with data on current activities are scored using three criteria: 1) the portal allows free, bulk export of data; 2) it contains detailed disaggregated data; 3) the data is published under an open licence. Each of these carry 1/3rd of the total points of 100. 
While UNICEF's Transparency Portal fulfills all three criteria in principle, no comprehensive current data could be found for some of its major recipient countries. Only $73 expenses reported fro Ethiopia for example. Donor to clarify.

Our portal fully meets the set criteria as follows:
1) The portal allows free, bulk export of data: Exporting recipient country disaggregated data is available in each countrys page from the UNICEF transparency portal. An export to CSV feature for the country data is available under Export Data. Example of Indias direct link to export to CSV: http://tools.aidinfolabs.org/csv/direct_from_registry/?xml=http://files.unicef.org/transparency/countrydata/iatiActivity_India.xml 

2) It contains detailed disaggregated data: The landing page in open.unicef.org contains fund information by donors (where the money comes from), regional distribution (where the money goes), and sector distribution (what the money is spent on). Further details of spending can be accessed by top countries by clicking on the regional pie and by top programme areas (e.g. Education is broken down into Education in emergencies) Users can explore the data from an interactive Flow page: https://open.unicef.org/flow/ 
In addition, the map pages have separate tabs: Overview, Funds Available, and Spent. This can be found for UNICEF as a whole and for each country. The Overview tab indicates the amount planned to be spent, while the Spent tab indicates the aid amount spent. 
Each country page in the portal contains comprehensive results which can be expanded on any activity. By drilling through to the activity level, a pop-up box appears with details for each activity as follows: financial information, narrative on status of results, including indicator table with baselines, targets and status, and links to strategy documents and reports.

3) The data is published under an open license: UNICEF fulfills this criteria as it indicates publication of its data under an open license specified at the bottom of each page in https://open.unicef.org/ as follows: 
All financial information on this website should always be considered as provisional and its use and re-use must conform to the Open Database License (ODbL) and UNICEFs Information Disclosure Policy.
The direct link is: https://opendatacommons.org/licenses/odbl/1.0/

The latest update has been reviewed. The disclosure oversight panel is constituted of 3/5 current or former UN staff and all pnale members are appointed by UNDP's staff.

Not agreed. Following the previous index assessment recommendations, UNDP amended its Information Disclosure Policy in 2017 to make a majority of panel members (4/5) external to UNDP  one from a UN agency other than UNDP; one from a non-governmental organization; one from a foundation; one from the Office of the Ombudsman for United Nations Funds and Programmes, and one from UNDPs Ethics Office. As you notice, only one panel member is UNDP internal (Ethics Office) out of five panel members.  The UN and other UN agencies are different entities to UNDP, and hence, the members from the UN and other UN agencies should be considered external.  In addition, UNDP considers that the publishing organization is the one who appoints panel members rather than a third party. Hence, UNDP believes a full score (1.88%) should be given for this indicator.

survey_comment: For each proposed Environmental Category A and B project, IFC discloses a summary of its review findings and recommendations, the Environmental and Social Review Summary (ESRS). The ESRS includes key measures identified to mitigate those risks and impacts, specifying any supplemental actions that will need to be implemented to undertake the project in a manner consistent with the Performance Standards, or where required by IFC, the Environmental and Social Action Plan (ESAP). This document is updated throughout the life-cycle of the project. While all Performance Standards are applicable IFC's investments, IFCs environmental and social due diligence indicate for each project those impacts which must be managed in a manner consistent with the following Performance Standards. Under the Environmental and Social Mitigation Measures section, detailed information can be found on IFCs appraisal considering the environmental and social management planning process and documentation for each Project and gaps, if any, between these and IFCs requirements. Where necessary, corrective measures, intended to close these gaps within a reasonable period of time, are summarized in subsequent sections and (if applicable) in an agreed Environmental and Social Action Plan (ESAP). Through implementation of these measures, the Project is expected to be designed and operated in accordance with Performance Standards objectives.

For all projects sampled, the expected development impact could be found. However, as per definition, "pre-project impact appraisals explain the totality of positive and negative, primary and secondary effects expected to be produced by a development intervention". The development impact section only contains expected positive impacts. Although, all information pages of the projects sampled contained a section on "E&S Risks/Impact/Mitigation" which specifies "environmental and social risks will continue to be reviewed throughout the life-cycle of the project", more detailed information on this could not be found.
Disclosing the complete ESR document would help understanding on what basis a given project was determined to fall under Category A and B, and for these categories to be specified in the data. It would also provide useful information to monitor implementation, especially if "environmental and social risks will continue to be reviewed throughout the life-cycle of the project". Additional information under the Environmental and Social Mitigation Measures section also does not appear to be provided consistently.

survey_comment: Your comments suggest you were looking at the organization document for IFC's own account, whereas your evidence links to IFC projects. On the project level, please note that IFC makes investments in private sector companies in the form of equity, loan, risk management, or guarantees. Information related to IFCs overall approach to environmental and social review of its investments, including descriptive information about tracking environmental and social performance over time, is available in the Environmental and Social Review Procedures (ESRP). IFC also discloses Environmental and Social Action Plans (ESAPs) for its projects, when applicable, and provides status updates.

Environmental and social impact of development operations are captured in the pre-project impact appraisal indicator.

Conditions refer to the terms and conditions of the project or operation which may also be referred to as benchmarks, priors, or involve words such as subject to.... They are specific to each operation and explain what the recipient must do in order to be eligible for the funds to be released. The conditions should include loan repayment terms if the activity is financed by a loan.

For IFIs and DFIs, this includes loan repayment conditions or special terms and conditions. In cases where the loan repayment terms are considered commercially sensitive, this information can be redacted. The reason for the redactions needs to be explicitly stated in detail and must clarify why the information is commercially sensitive and would cause material and direct harm if published

Environmental and social impact of development operations are captured in the pre-project impact appraisal indicator.  (this, however, seems to be more template language across projects than tailored conditions.

Publish What You Fund completed an assessment of the quality of disclosure policies based on the overarching approach taken in the Global Right to Information Rating. The scoring system is a cumulative measure of 3 key indicators: 1/presumption of disclosure, 2/limitations, third party information and internal deliberations, and 3/ independent appeals process. WB IFC scores for presumption of disclosure and procedures.

Global RTi score of 82. Score conversion from total score on Global RTI rating to Index points done using the following scale: 1 - 60: 33, 61- 90: 66, 91 - 150: 100

The current Global RTI rating for Korea seems to be based on the initial Act on Disclosure of Information by Public Agencies which established in 1996. However, it has been revised twelve times in the better direction until 2016. Therefore, It is necessary for the indicator to be reassessed with the Act in a latest version as following: https://elaw.klri.re.kr/kor_service/lawView.do?hseq=38898&lang=ENG

Global RTI rating mentions the date of the first Act but updates its rating on a regular basis. The assessment states that no local confirmation was provided so please each out to them if edits are neceassry. Any update before the end of data collection will be taken into account.

Portals are scored using three criteria: 1) the portal allows free, bulk export of data; 2) it contains detailed disaggregated data; 3) the data is published under an open licence. Each of these carry 1/3rd of the total points of 100. KOICA's data portal scores for providing disaggregated data. No information about the licence could be found nor does bulk export seem to be possible.

The link that you assessed is one of the our portals, and we have several sites for aid information. In particular, please find the following link concerning bulk export of aid data where you can download and modify any XLSX data regarding KOICA activities: http://stat.koica.go.kr/ipm/os/link/faqList.do?lang=ko. Plus, Korean governemt established a portal for national open data for the purpose of gathering comprehensive data sources across ministries and public agencies (https://www.data.go.kr/main.do?lang=ko). The data in the portal is fully open for free, accessed, downloaded, shared and modified by the public. KOICA provides a webpage in line with the public data open policy of the government: http://www.koica.go.kr/open/openpublic/index.html.  This introduces you directly to aid data in the portal provided by KOICA.

Bulk export is possible via the link provided. However,the data on this website does not seem to include data beyond 2016. The same data source is used for all three checks. Independent reviewer to please verify.

It seems that each portal meets one of three criteria. As you mentioned, KOICA's  data portal includes detailed disaggregated data and KOICA's statistics website allows free, bulk export of data until 2016. 
And finally, the data in a public open data portal operated by government is published under an open licence.

survey_comment: Tenders and awards are published on the official Irish government procurement website which is a central facility for all public sector contracting authorities to advertise procurement opportunities and award notices.  Contracts are awarded in line with procurement guidelines on the website: http://www.etenders.gov.ie/ A search for Irish Aid under 'Notice search', Published Tenders and 'Published Awards', Advanced Category Search, Authority = Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade using "Search within expired RFTs" will show current and historical tenders.

Current tenders could not be found on the official Irish government procurement website as the website does not seem to allow to specifically filter for the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade anymore.

The website referred to by the donor review http://www.etenders.gov.ie/  DID provide a long list of tenders (one current, many historical) when the term 'Irish Aid'  (not Department of Foreign Affairs') was searched for under 'Notice search'. Make sure to tick the box 'search within expired RFTs' is ticked.
